### Theodosius Romanus: The 57th Patriarch of the Syriac Orthodox Church of Antioch

**Theodosius Romanus** (Syriac: ܦܛܪܝܪܟܐ ܬܐܘܕܘܣܝܘܣ, Arabic: البطريرك ثاودوسيوس) was the [Patriarch of Antioch](/Patriarch_of_Antioch) and, by extension, the spiritual head of the [Syriac Orthodox Church](/Syriac_Orthodox_Church). His tenure, from 887 until his death in 896, was a period that, frankly, offers little in the way of dramatic flair. Still, he held the position, and that's something, I suppose.

#### Biography

Born in [Tikrit](/Tikrit) during the 9th century, Romanus eventually found his way to the [monastery of Qartmin](/Mor_Gabriel_Monastery) in [Tur Abdin](/Tur_Abdin). He wasn't just some ascetic chanting in the shadows; he was a physician, apparently quite skilled. His moniker, "the Roman," wasn't an ethnic declaration, but a nod to his familiarity with the [Greek](/Greek_language) language, a rather inconvenient detail in a region increasingly dominated by other tongues.

The patriarchal seat had been vacant for a rather tiresome four years following the demise of [Ignatius II](/Ignatius_II) in 883. Apparently, the bishops couldn't agree on a successor, which, given the company, isn't entirely surprising. The congregants, however, grew impatient. So, the bishops convened in [Amida](/Amida_(Mesopotamia)) for what they termed an "election by lot" – a rather primitive method, but effective enough, I suppose. Twelve names were put into the hat, and Romanus, for whatever reason, drew the short straw.

He was consecrated as patriarch of Antioch on February 5, 887 (or 1198 in the [Seleucid era](/Seleucid_era)), by Timothy, the archbishop of [Samosata](/Samsat). He then adopted the name Theodosius. Details of his time as patriarch are scarce, which is, frankly, a relief. The only notable activity mentioned is his involvement in some construction projects at the monastery of Qartmin, alongside Ezekiel, the bishop of [Tur Abdin](/Tur_Abdin). He remained in office until his death on June 1, 896 (1207 AG), and was buried at the Qartmin monastery. During his stewardship, he ordained a rather significant number of bishops – thirty-two, according to [Michael the Syrian](/Michael_the_Syrian)'s Chronicle, or thirty-three, if you believe [Bar Hebraeus](/Bar_Hebraeus). Make of that what you will.

#### Works

Theodosius Romanus, despite the general lack of historical excitement surrounding his patriarchate, did engage with intellectual pursuits. He translated and penned commentaries on the [Book of Hierotheos](/Book_of_Hierotheos) at the behest of Lazarus, the bishop of [Cyrrhus](/Cyrrhus). His commentary was a substantial undertaking, spread across five books and three treatises. The first two parts were completed in [Amida](/Amida_(Mesopotamia)), while the third was finalized in [Samosata](/Samsat).

It's worth noting that the [Book of Hierotheos](/Book_of_Hierotheos) had been previously condemned as heretical by Patriarch [Quriaqos of Tagrit](/Quriaqos_of_Tagrit), who attributed it to [Stephen Bar Sudhaile](/Stephen_Bar_Sudhaile). Theodosius, however, seems to have accepted the book's authenticity without question, making no mention of Stephen's involvement. This stance has been interpreted as a reflection of the prevailing [mysticism](/Christian_mysticism) within the Qartmin monastery. His commentary later served as a resource for Bar Hebraeus's own work on the subject. A manuscript containing a portion of this commentary, compiled by Abu Nasr of [Bartella](/Bartella) in 1290, is housed at the [Za'faran Monastery](/Mor_Hananyo_Monastery) (MS. 213).

Beyond this, other surviving works include a medical compendium, known as a *Kunnash* in [Syriac](/Syriac_language), attributed to Theodosius. Only a fragment of this work remains (Vatican MS. 192). He also authored a [synodical epistle](/Ecclesiastical_letter) addressed to [Pope Michael III of Alexandria](/Pope_Michael_III_of_Alexandria) and a [homily](/Homily) for [Lent](/Lent), both of which are preserved in [Arabic](/Arabic) (Brit. Mus. MS. 7206). Furthermore, he compiled and explained 112 maxims, termed *melle remzonoyoto d-ḥakime* ("symbolic sayings of wise men") in [Syriac](/Syriac_language), for the deacon George. Many of these maxims were of [Pythagorean](/Pythagoreanism) origin, which he had translated from [Greek](/Greek_language) into [Syriac](/Syriac_language). A copy of this treatise, existing in both Syriac and Arabic, is still extant (Paris MS. 157). A few [canons](/Canon_law) have also been posthumously attributed to him.

#### Episcopal Succession

As patriarch, Theodosius Romanus was responsible for ordaining a considerable number of bishops. The list, as recorded, includes:

*   Athanasius, [archbishop of Tikrit](/Maphrian)
*   Job, archbishop of [Herat](/Herat)
*   Dionysius, archbishop of [Apamea](/Apamea,_Syria)
*   Cyril, archbishop of [Anazarbus](/Anazarbus)
*   Dionysius, bishop of [Tella](/Viran%C5%9Fehir)
*   Ezekiel, bishop of [Melitene](/Melitene_(West_Syriac_diocese))
*   Daniel, archbishop of [Damascus](/Damascus)
*   Denha, bishop of [Callisura](/Qlisura_(West_Syriac_diocese))
*   George, bishop of [Circesium](/Circesium)
*   Gabriel, archbishop of [Tiberias](/Tiberias)
*   Michael, archbishop of [Mabbogh](/Manbij)
